\begin{flushleft}
1. Representations of Lie groups.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Representation theory of groups is a vast subject. Many of the aspects of this theory
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
that are of interest in Harmonic Analysis, and, in particular, of that body of ideas
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and techniques that might be collectively referred to as Applied Harmonic Analysis,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
can be studied within the class of locally compact and second countable topological
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
groups, a family whose nickname in the group-theory jargon is {``}lcsc''. To be honest,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
though, most interesting examples belong to the smaller and nicer class of Lie groups,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
for which not only much more is known, but that also have the additional feature of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
possessing a geometric nature that allows, for instance, to speak about dimension. For
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
this reason we work mostly with this family, even though we shall by no means use the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
full force of the representation thereof. On the reader's side, we shall take for granted
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
basic knowledge of diﬀerential geometry.
\end{flushleft}


1





\newpage
2





\begin{flushleft}
The use of representations
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
1.1. Locally compact groups. We start with some fundamental deﬁnitions and results. For a detailed account on these matters the reader may consult [F1].
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Deﬁnition 1.1. A topological group is a group G endowed with a topology relative to
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
which the group operations
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(g, h) $\rightarrow$ gh,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
g $\rightarrow$ g $-$1
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
are continuous as maps G × G $\rightarrow$ G and G $\rightarrow$ G, respectively. G is locally compact
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
if every point has a compact neighborhood. We shall also assume our groups to be
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Hausdorﬀ.
\end{flushleft}


A Borel measure $\mu$ on the topological space $E$ is called a Radon measure if, \\
(i) it is ﬁnite on compact sets;
(ii) it is outer regular on the Borel sets: for every Borel set E
\begin{equation}
 \mu(E) = inf\{\mu(U) : U \supset E, U open \} 
\end{equation}





\begin{flushleft}
(iii) it is inner regular on the open sets: for every open set U
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\mu$(U ) = sup\{$\mu$(K) : K $\subset$ E, K compact \}.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Deﬁnition 1.3. A left Haar measure on the topological group G is a non zero Radon
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
measure $\mu$ such that $\mu$(xE) = $\mu$(E) for every Borel set E $\subset$ G and every x $\in$ G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Similarly for right Haar measures.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Of course, the prototype of Haar measure is the Lebesgue measure on the additive
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
group Rd , which is invariant under left (and right) translations.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 1.4. Every locally compact group G has a left Haar measure $\lambda$, which is
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
essentially unique in the sense that if $\mu$ is any other left Haar measure, then there
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
exists a positive constant C such that $\mu$ = c$\lambda$.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
If we ﬁx a left Haar measure $\lambda$ on G, then for any x $\in$ G the measure $\lambda$x deﬁned
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\lambda$x (E) = $\lambda$(Ex)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is again a left Haar measure (here Ex = \{ex : e $\in$ E\}). Therefore there must exist a
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
positive real number, denoted ∆(x) such that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\lambda$x = ∆(x)$\lambda$.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The function ∆ : G $\rightarrow$ R+ is called the modular function.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 1.5. Let G be a locally compact group.The modular function ∆ : G $\rightarrow$ R+
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is a continuous homomorphism into the multiplicative group R+ . Furthermore, for
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
every f $\in$ L1 (G, $\lambda$) we have
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
f (xy) dx = ∆(y)$-$1
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
G
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
f (x) dx.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
G
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
\newpage
Representations of Lie groups
\end{flushleft}





3





\begin{flushleft}
In the Section 1.2.4 below we give some examples in the context of Lie groups. A
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
group for which every left Haar measure is also a right Haar measure, hence for which
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the modular function is identically equal to one, is called unimodular. Large classes
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
of groups are unimodular, such as the abelian, compact, nilpotent, semisimple and
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
reductive groups. Nevetherless, in Applied Harmonic Analysis non-unimodular groups
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
play a prominent role, such as the aﬃne group {``}ax + b'' that we shall deﬁne in the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
next section.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
1.2. Lie groups and Lie algebras. In this section we recall, without proofs, some
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
basic facts about Lie groups and Lie algebras. For a concise and eﬀective exposition,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
see [W]. Classical references with a wider scope are [K1] and [V].
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Deﬁnition 1.6. A Lie group G is a C $\infty$ (smooth or diﬀerentiable) manifold endowed
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
with a group structure such that the group operations (g, h) $\rightarrow$ gh and g $\rightarrow$ g $-$1 are
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
smooth, that is, C $\infty$ .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Examples. 1. Clearly, Rd is an additive, abelian Lie group. Similarly Cd , identiﬁed
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
with R2d as manifolds.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
2. The sphere S 1 = \{ei$\theta$ : $\theta$ $\in$ [0, 2$\pi$)\} is an abelian compact Lie group. A famous
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
theorem states that the only other spheres that are Lie groups are S 3 and S 7 .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
3. The multiplicative group GL(d, R) of invertible matrices is a Lie group. Indeed,
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
it is an open submanifold of Rd with the global coordinates xij that assign to a matrix
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
its ij --th entry. If y, z $\in$ GL(d, R), then xij (yz) and xij (y $-$1 ) are rational functions of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
\{xij (y), xij (z)\} and of \{xij (y)\}, respectively, with non vanishing denominator. Hence
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
they are smooth functions.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
As we shall mention brieﬂy, all closed subgroups of GL(d, R) are nice Lie groups.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Most notably, from our point of view, the symplectic group Sp(d, R) to be deﬁned
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
below.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
4. The aﬃne group {``}ax + b''. There are several possible versions of this group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Let G = R+ × R as a manifold. One can visualize it as the right half plane. The
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
multiplication is obtained by thinking of the pair (a, b), with a $>$ 0 and b $\in$ R, as
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
identifying the aﬃne transformation of the real line given by x $\rightarrow$ ax + b, whence the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
name. The composition of maps
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
x $\rightarrow$ ax + b $\rightarrow$ a (ax + b) + b = [a a]x + [a b + b]
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
yields the product rule
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(a , b )(a, b) = (a a, a b + b).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Evidently, both functions a a and a b + b are smooth in the global coordinates on G,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
which is then a Lie group. Evidently, G is connected. When speaking of the {``}ax + b''
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
group we refer to this group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
A non-connected version arises by taking a $\in$ R instead of a $>$ 0. Yet another
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
slightly diﬀerent construction comes from thinking of the pair (a, b) as identifying the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
aﬃne transformation x $\rightarrow$ a(x + b). This point of view yields both a connected and a
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
non-connected Lie group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
4. The Heisenberg group Hd . We refer to the next section for the explicit deﬁnition.
\end{flushleft}





\newpage
4





\begin{flushleft}
The use of representations
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Deﬁnition 1.7. A Lie algebra g over the ﬁeld1 K is a K-vector space endowed with
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
a bilinear operation [·, ·] : g × g $\rightarrow$ g, called bracket, such that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
i) [X, Y ] = $-$[Y, X] for every X, Y $\in$ g,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
ii) [X, [Y, Z]] = [[X, Y ], Z] + [Y, [X, Z]] for every X, Y, Z $\in$ g.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Item ii), oterwise known as the Jacobi identity, should be thought of as an analogous
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
version of the derivative of the product. Indeed, if for any X $\in$ g we put
\end{flushleft}


(1.1)





\begin{flushleft}
ad X : g $\rightarrow$ g,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
ad X(Y ) = [X, Y ]
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
the Jacobi identity may be formulated:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
ad X([Y, Z]) = [ad X(Y ), Z] + [Y, ad X(Z)].
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
If V is a K-vector space, the set End(V ) of all linear maps of V into itself is a Lie
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
algebra under the commutator [$\phi$, $\psi$] = $\phi$$\psi$ $-$ $\psi$$\phi$ as bracket. With this structure
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
understood, it is denoted by gl(V ).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Let G be a Lie group, and let X(G) denote the C $\infty$ (G)-module of the smooth vector
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
ﬁleds on G. Denote by lg : G $\rightarrow$ G the left translation by g $\in$ G, that is lg (h) = gh.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
A vector ﬁeld X $\in$ X(G) is called left invariant on G if for every g, h $\in$ G it holds
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(lg )∗h Xh = Xgh ,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
where (lg )∗h : Th (G) $\rightarrow$ Th (G) denotes the diﬀerential of lg at h and Th (G) is the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
tangent space to G at h. The set of all left invariant vector ﬁelds on G will be
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
denoted L(G).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 1.8. Let G be a Lie group and denote by L(G) the set of left invariant
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
vector ﬁelds on G. Then:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
i) L(G) is an R-vector space and the map $\alpha$ : L(G) $\rightarrow$ Te (G) deﬁned by $\alpha$(X) =
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Xe is a vector space isomorphism between L(G) and the tangent space to G at
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the identity e $\in$ G. Consequently, dim L(G) = dim Te (G) = dim G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
ii) The commutator [X, Y ] = X ◦ Y $-$ Y ◦ X of two left invariant vector ﬁelds
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is again a left invariant vector ﬁeld. With this bracket, L(G) becomes a Lie
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
algebra, which will be called the Lie algebra of G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
1.2.1. Homomorphisms. Take now two Lie groups, G ed H . A map ϕ : G $\rightarrow$ H is a
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Lie group homomorphism if it is a group homomorphism (hence if ϕ(xy) = ϕ(x)ϕ(y)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
for every x, y $\in$ G and if ϕ(e) = e, the identities of G and H , respectively) and if
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
it is a C $\infty$ map of smooth manifolds. We say that ϕ is a Lie group isomorphism if
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
it is a diﬀeomorphism. An isomorphism of G onto itself is called an automorphism.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Observe that the set of automorphisms of a ﬁnite dimensional R--vector space V has
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
a natural structure of Lie group, because if a basis is selected, then the group of all
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
linear invertible maps may be identiﬁed with the Lie group of invertible matrices.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
This group is denoted by Aut(V ). As we shall see in Section 1.3, a homomorphism
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\pi$ : G $\rightarrow$ Aut(V ) is a ﬁnite dimensional representation of G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
1Here
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
mostly K = R but one may also think of the case K = C .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
\newpage
Representations of Lie groups
\end{flushleft}





5





\begin{flushleft}
If g and h sare both real Lie algebras, a linear map $\psi$ : g $\rightarrow$ h for which $\psi$([X, Y ]) =
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
[$\psi$(X), $\psi$(Y )] is a Lie algebra homomorphism. Further, if $\psi$ is a linear isomorphism,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
then it is called a Lie algebra isomorphism. If h = gl(W ) is the Lie algebra of all
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
endomorphisms of a vector space W , a Lie algebra homomorphism $\psi$ : g $\rightarrow$ h is called
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
a representation of g on W . This is the case of the homomorphism X $\rightarrow$ ad X , which
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
deﬁnes the adjoint representation of g, a representation of g on itself.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Let ϕ : G $\rightarrow$ H be a Lie group homomorphism. Its diﬀerential ϕ∗e : Te (G) $\rightarrow$ Te (H)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is a linear map. By the natural identiﬁcations Te (G) L(G) and Te (H) L(H), ϕ∗e
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
induces a linear map L(G) $\rightarrow$ L(H) denoted dϕ. More precisely, if X $\in$ L(G), then
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
dϕ(X) is the unique left invariant vector ﬁeld on G such that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(dϕ(X))e = ϕ∗e Xe .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The following result clariﬁes matters.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 1.9. Let ϕ : G $\rightarrow$ H be a Lie group homomorphism. Then ϕ∗g Xg =
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(dϕ(X))ϕ(X) for every X $\in$ L(G) and dϕ is a Lie algebra homomorphism.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Take again a Lie group homomorphism i : G $\rightarrow$ H and assume that i is injective
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and that also its diﬀerential is injective in every point (such a map is called an injective
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
immersion). In this case the pair (i, H) is called a Lie subgroup of G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 1.10. Let G be a Lie group with Lie algebra g and take a Lie subalgebra h of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
g. Then there exists a connected Lie subgroup (i, H) of G, unique up to isomorphisms,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
such that di(L(H)) = h. Therefore there is a bijective correspondence between the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
connected Lie subgroup of a Lie group and the subalgebras of its Lie algebra.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The theory of covering groups is also very important, and relevant in the present
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
context, but we content ourselves with the observation that every connected Lie group
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
has a simply connected covering that admits the structure of Lie group and for which
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the covering homomorphism is a Lie group homomorphism. Furthermore, a Lie group
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
homomorphism ϕ : G $\rightarrow$ H is a covering map if and only if dϕ is a Lie algebra
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
isomorphism. The following theorem is of central importance in the theory of Lie
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
groups.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 1.11. Let G1 and G2 be two Lie groups with Lie algebras g1 and g2 , respectively, and let $\lambda$ : g1 $\rightarrow$ g2 be a Lie algebra homomorphism. Then there cannot be
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
more than one Lie group homomorphism ϕ : G1 $\rightarrow$ G2 such that dϕ = $\lambda$. If G1 is
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
simply connected, then such a ϕ exists.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
1.2.2. Exponential mapping. We now review in some detail the deﬁnition of the ﬁundamental map linking the group and its Lie algebra, namely the exponential mapping
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
exp : g $\rightarrow$ G. Let R be the additive Lie group of real numbers. Its Lie algebra is
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
one-dimensional and is generated by the vector ﬁeld dt . Take now a Lie group G with
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Lie algebra g, and ﬁx X $\in$ g. The map
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\tau$ $\rightarrow$ $\tau$ X,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\tau$ $\in$R
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
dt
\end{flushleft}





