\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
X $\in$ g.
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
The map exp : g $\rightarrow$ G is called the exponential mapping. From (1.3) it follows that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\xi$X (t) = exp(tX),
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
exp 0 = e.
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
t $\in$ R, X $\in$ g
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
It is easy to check that if X $\in$ g e x $\in$ G sare ﬁxed, the map t $\rightarrow$ x exp(tX) deﬁnes
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the integral curve relative to X passing through x. Hence, for every C $\infty$ -function f
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
in a neighborhood of x we have
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
d
\end{flushleft}


(1.5)


\begin{flushleft}
Xx (f ) =
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
f (x exp tX).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
dt t=0
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
An immediate consequence of the fact that $\xi$X is a homomorphism are the formulae
\end{flushleft}


(1.6)





\begin{flushleft}
exp(t + s)X = exp tX exp sX
\end{flushleft}





(1.7)





\begin{flushleft}
exp($-$tX) = (exp tX)$-$1 .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
The following formulae require some harder work:
\end{flushleft}


(1.8)





1


\begin{flushleft}
exp tX exp tY = exp\{t(X + Y ) + 2 t2 [X, Y ] + O(t3 )\}
\end{flushleft}





(1.9)





\begin{flushleft}
exp($-$tX)exp($-$tY ) exp tX exp tY = exp\{t2 [X, Y ] + O(t3 )\}
\end{flushleft}





(1.10)





\begin{flushleft}
exp tX exp tY exp($-$tX) = exp\{tY + t2 [X, Y ] + O(t3 )\}.
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Formula (1.8) is the well-known di Baker--Campbell--Hausdorﬀ formula. The exponential map is in general neither injective nor surjective, but it is locally very nice:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 1.12. The exponential map is C $\infty$ and its diﬀerntial at zero is the identity
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
map of g. Consequently, exp establishes a diﬀeomorphism of a neighborhood of 0 $\in$ g
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
onto a a neighborhood of e $\in$ G.
\end{flushleft}





