\begin{flushleft}
The following is fundamental.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 1.13. Let ϕ : G $\rightarrow$ H be a Lie group homomorphism with diﬀerential
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
dϕ : g $\rightarrow$ h. Then, for every X $\in$ g
\end{flushleft}


(1.11)





\begin{flushleft}
ϕ(exp X) = exp(dϕX).
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
By means of the previous result it is easy to show the next one, which is of great
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
practical use because it allows to calculate the Lie algebra of a subgroup of G as a
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
subalgebra of the Lie algebra of G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 1.14. Let H be a Lie subgroup of the Lie group G and let h $\subset$ g be the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
corresponding Lie algebras. Fix X $\in$ g. If X $\in$ h, then exp tX $\in$ H for every t $\in$ R.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Conversely, if exp tX $\in$ H for every t $\in$ R, then X $\in$ h.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Reﬁning the above result one obtains the next, which is very useful when dealing
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
with the classical matrix groups and algebras.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 1.15. Let A be an abstract subgroup of the Lie group G and let a be a
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
vector subspace of the Lie algebra g of G. Let U be a neighborhood of 0 $\in$ g diﬀeomorphic via exp to the neighborood V of e $\in$ G. Suppose that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
exp(U $\cap$ a) = A $\cap$ V.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Then, endowed with the relative topology, A is a Lie subgroup of G and a is its Lie
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
algebra.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Examples. The set of all n × n real matrices endowed with the bracket [A, B] =
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
AB$-$BA is a Lie algebra, and, as any vector space, a smooth manifold with coordinates
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
given by any choice of a basis. Denote by g the Lie algebra of GL(d, R) and let
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\alpha$ : gl(d, R)e $\rightarrow$ gl(d, R) the canonical identiﬁcation of the tangent space at the identity
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
e $\in$ gl(d, R) with gl(d, R). Thus, if v $\in$ gl(d, R)e
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\alpha$(v)ij = v(xij ).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Since GL(d, R)e = gl(d, R)e , there is a natural map:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\beta$ : g $\rightarrow$ gl(d, R),
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
$\beta$(X) = $\alpha$(Xe ).
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
It is easy to see (exercise) that $\beta$ is a Lie algebra isomorphism. The ordinary matrix
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
exponentiation
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
A $\rightarrow$ eA
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
satisﬁes all the properties of the exponential mapping and it thus coincides with it,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
from gl(d, R) into GL(d, R). We recall also that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
det eA = etr A .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Take now a neighborhood U of 0 $\in$ gl(d, C) diﬀeomorphic under exp to the neighborhood V of I $\in$ GL(d, C). We now prove that the Lie algebra of Sp(d, R) is sp(d, R),
\end{flushleft}


