\begin{flushleft}
We conclude this section with two important results.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 1.16. (Cartan) Let G be a Lie group and let A be a closed subgroup of G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Then A has a unique smooth (in fact analytic) structure that makes it a Lie subgroup
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
of G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 1.17. Let G be a connected Lie group with Lie algebra g and let ϕ : G $\rightarrow$ H
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
be a Lie group homomorphism of G into the Lie group H , whose Lie algebra is h.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Then:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
i) ker(ϕ) is a closed Lie subgroup of G with Lie algebra ker(dϕ);
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
ii) ϕ(G) is a Lie subgroup of H with Lie algebra dϕ(g) $\in$ h.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
1.2.3. Adjoint representations. The most important ﬁnite dimensional representation
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
of a Lie group G is certainly the adjoint representation, which acts on its Lie algebra
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
gg . Passiamo inﬁne a descrivere la pi` importante rappresentazione (ﬁnito dimensionu
\end{flushleft}


