\begin{flushleft}
1.3. Representation theory. Let H1 and H2 be two Hilbert spaces and suppose
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
that T : H1 $\rightarrow$ H2 is linear and bounded, that is T $\in$ B(H1 , H2 ). Recall that T is
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
an isometry if T u = u for every u $\in$ H1 . Since T u 2 = T u, T u = T ∗ T u, u
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
e u 2 = u, u , the polarition identity implies that T is an isometry if and only if
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
T ∗ T = idH1 . Hence, isometries are injective, but they are not necessarily surjective. A
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
bijective isometry is called a unitary map. If T is unitary, such is also T $-$1 and in this
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
case T T ∗ = idH2 . In particular if H1 = H2 = H, the set
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
U(H) = T $\in$ B(H) : T is unitary
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
forms a group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Let now G be a Lie2 group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Deﬁnition 1.22. A unitary representation of G on the Hilbert space H is a group
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
homomorphism $\pi$ : G $\rightarrow$ U(H) continuous in the strong operator topology. This means:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
i) $\pi$(gh) = $\pi$(g)$\pi$(h) for every g, h $\in$ G;
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
ii) $\pi$(g $-$1 ) = $\pi$(g)$-$1 = $\pi$(g)∗ for every g $\in$ G;
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
iii) g $\rightarrow$ $\pi$(g)u is continuous from G to H, for every u $\in$ H.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Observe that from the equality $\pi$(g)u $-$ $\pi$(h)u = $\pi$(hg $-$1 )u $-$ u it follows that it
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is enough to check iii) for g = e, the identity of G.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Examples. 1. Let G = R be additive group and H = C. For every s $\in$ R we
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
deﬁne the function $\chi$s (t) = eits and we identify the complex number eits with the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
multiplication operator on C deﬁned by z $\rightarrow$ zeits . Clearly, $\chi$s : R $\rightarrow$ U(C) is a
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
unitary representation, because
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
