\begin{flushleft}
2. The Heisenberg group and its representations
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
2.1. The group and its Lie algebra. We shall denote by Hd the Heisenberg group,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
namely the smooth diﬀerentiable manifold Rd × Rd × R endowed with the product
\end{flushleft}


(2.30)





\begin{flushleft}
((q, p, t)(q , p , t ) = (q + q , p + p , t + t $-$ 1 ( tqp $-$ tpq)).
\end{flushleft}


2





\begin{flushleft}
Let $\omega$ : R2d × R2d $\rightarrow$ R be the standard symplectic form
\end{flushleft}


(2.31)





\begin{flushleft}
$\omega$(x, x ) = txJx,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
J=
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
0 Id
\end{flushleft}


.


\begin{flushleft}
$-$Id 0
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Upon writing x = x(q,p) = t [q, p] $\in$ R2d , we may formulate (2.30) in terms of the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
symplectic form, namely:
\end{flushleft}


1


(2.32)


\begin{flushleft}
((x, t)(x , t ) = (x + x , t + t $-$ $\omega$(x, x )).
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
It is clear from (2.30) and (2.32) that the product in Hd is given by functions that are
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
C $\infty$ in the global R2d+1 coordinates (q, p, t). Furthermore, one checks at once that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(x, t)$-$1 = ($-$x, $-$t),
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
another C $\infty$ formula. Hence Hd is a Lie group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Exercises. 1) Prove that the center of Hd is Z = \{(0, t) : t $\in$ R\}.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
2) Write explicitely the inner conjugation ig (h) = ghg $-$1 .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
3) Prove that L1 = \{(q, 0, t) : q $\in$ Rd , t $\in$ R\} and L2 = \{(0, p, t) : p $\in$ Rd , t $\in$ R\}
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
are two Lie subgroups of Hd which are mutually isomorphic but not conjugate.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
We next want to identify the Lie algebra hd of Hd in terms of left invariant vector
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
