\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the celebrated Heisenberg commutation relations. Therefore, identifying R2d+1 with
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
hd via the map (x1 , . . . , xd , y1 , . . . , yd , z) $\rightarrow$ d (xj Qj + yj Pj ) + zT , we obtain the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
j=1
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
following Lie algebra structure on R2d+1 :
\end{flushleft}


(2.33)





\begin{flushleft}
[(X, z), (X , z )] = (0, $-$$\omega$(X, X )).
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
From this commutator rule, one sees immediately that [A, [B, C]] = 0 for every choice
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
of A, B and C in hd . Similarly, any higher order bracket vanishes. This fact can
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
be expressed technically by saying that hd is a two-step nilpotent Lie algebra. The
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Baker--Campbell--Hausdorﬀ formula becomes A, B $\in$ hd
\end{flushleft}


1


\begin{flushleft}
exp A exp B = exp(A + B + [A, B])
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
and since for A = (X, z) and B = (X , z ) it holds
\end{flushleft}


1


1


\begin{flushleft}
A + B + [A, B] = (X + X , z + z $-$ $\omega$(X, X )),
\end{flushleft}


2


2


\begin{flushleft}
which coincides with the product (2.32), we infer that
\end{flushleft}


(2.34)





\begin{flushleft}
exp(X, z) = (X, z)
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
