\begin{flushleft}
Automorphisms. Given a Lie group G with Lie algebra g it is often interesting
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(and many times diﬃcult) to understand their automorphism groups. An automorphism of the Lie group G is an invertible group homomorphism. Unravelling this
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
deﬁnition, this means a bijective smooth map ϕ : G $\rightarrow$ G preserving products, namely
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
satisfying ϕ(xy) = ϕ(x)ϕ(y) and ϕ(e) = e. The collection of all such maps is, in
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
turn, a group under composition, denoted Aut(G). Under favorable circumstances3,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and surely this is the case for Hd , the group Aut(G) has itself a natural structure of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Lie group, though we shall not insist on this. Notice that since we have identiﬁed Hd
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
with R2d+1 , we are in fact looking at maps ϕ : R2d+1 $\rightarrow$ R2d+1 .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
3As
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
it was shown by Hochschild in 1951, it is enough that the group of components of G is ﬁnitely
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
generated.
\end{flushleft}





\newpage
22





\begin{flushleft}
The use of representations
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Similarly, one may consider the automorphisms of g, namely the bijective linear
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
maps $\Phi$ : g $\rightarrow$ g satisfying $\Phi$([X, Y ]) = [$\Phi$(X), $\Phi$(Y )]. Again, under composition they
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
form a group, denoted by Aut(g). Since its elements are linear maps, Aut(g) is in fact
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
a (closed) subgroup of GL(d, R) in a natural fashion, where d is the dimension of g.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Hence Aut(g) can be given the structure of a Lie group without problems. Also, the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
diﬀerential dϕ of any ϕ $\in$ Aut(G) is easily seen to belong to Aut(g). This accounts for
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
an immersion of Aut(G) into Aut(g) whenever G is connected. When looking at the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Heisenberg group, things are even nicer, this, and the following results show exactly
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
how. The proofs and arguments below are from [F2].
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 2.1. Aut(Hd ) = Aut(hd ).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proof. Under our identiﬁcations, the group and algebra operations are related by:
\end{flushleft}


1


\begin{flushleft}
X · Y = X + Y + [X, Y ].
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
Take now $\alpha$ $\in$ Aut(hd ). Then
\end{flushleft}


1


1


\begin{flushleft}
$\alpha$(X + Y + [X, Y ]) = $\alpha$(X) + $\alpha$(Y ) + [$\alpha$(X), $\alpha$(Y )] = $\alpha$(X) · $\alpha$(Y )
\end{flushleft}


2


2


\begin{flushleft}
shows that $\alpha$ $\in$ Aut(Hd ). Conversely, let $\alpha$ $\in$ Aut(Hd ) and take X, Y $\in$ hd such that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
[X, Y ] = 0. Then
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\alpha$(X + Y ) = $\alpha$(X · Y )
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
= $\alpha$(X) · $\alpha$(Y )
\end{flushleft}


1


\begin{flushleft}
= $\alpha$(X) + $\alpha$(Y ) + [$\alpha$(X), $\alpha$(Y )]
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
= $\alpha$(Y · X)
\end{flushleft}


1


\begin{flushleft}
= $\alpha$(X) + $\alpha$(Y ) + [$\alpha$(Y ), $\alpha$(X)],
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
so that necessarily [$\alpha$(Y ), $\alpha$(X)] = 0 and therefore $\alpha$(X + Y ) = $\alpha$(X) + $\alpha$(Y ). In
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
particular, $\alpha$ is additive on one-dimensional subspaces and is continuous; hence it
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
commutes with scalar multiplication4. Therefore, if X, Y $\in$ R2n+1 and s $\in$ R
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
s2
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
s
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
s$\alpha$(X + Y + [X, Y ]) = $\alpha$(sX + sY + [X, Y ])
\end{flushleft}


2


2


\begin{flushleft}
= $\alpha$(sX · sY )
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
= s$\alpha$(X) s$\alpha$(Y )
\end{flushleft}


1


\begin{flushleft}
= s$\alpha$(X) + s$\alpha$(Y ) + s2 [$\alpha$(X), $\alpha$(Y )]
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
If we divide by s and let s $\rightarrow$ 0, we get that $\alpha$ is additive on the whole of R2d+1 ,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
namely that it is linear. The last equality with s = 1 yields $\alpha$([X, Y ]) = [$\alpha$(X), $\alpha$(Y )],
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
that is $\alpha$ $\in$ Aut(hd ), as desired.
\end{flushleft}


