\begin{flushleft}
2.2. The Schr¨dinger representation. Let $\pi$ be a unitary and irreducible repreo
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
sentation of H on the Hilbert space H. Then all the operators $\pi$(0, 0, t) are in I($\pi$)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
because the center of Hd consists of the elements of the form (0, 0, t). But then Schur's
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Lemma implies that there exists a complex number of modulus one, denoted $\chi$(t), such
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
that
\end{flushleft}


(2.36)





\begin{flushleft}
$\pi$(0, 0, t) = $\chi$(t)IH .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Hence t $\rightarrow$ $\chi$(t) is a continuous function from R into T that satisﬁes the equality
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\chi$(s + t) = $\chi$(s)$\chi$(t). Therefore there exists a unique $\lambda$ $\in$ R such that
\end{flushleft}


(2.37)





\begin{flushleft}
$\chi$(t) = ei$\lambda$t .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Now, if $\lambda$ = 0, then $\pi$(0, 0, t) = IH , so that Z $\subset$ ker $\pi$ and the representaion $\pi$ projects
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
onto a representation $\pi$ on the quotient Hd /Z
\end{flushleft}


˜


\begin{flushleft}
R2d . The representation $\pi$ is still
\end{flushleft}


˜


\begin{flushleft}
2d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
unitary and irreducible. But R is abelian and hence all the operators $\pi$ (x, y), with
\end{flushleft}


˜


\begin{flushleft}
(x, y) $\in$ R2d commute with each other and therefore belong to I($\pi$). But then they are
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
multiples of the identity on H and every one-dimensional subspace of H is a proper
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\pi$ --invariant subspace. Since $\pi$ is irreducible, necessarily dim H = 1, namely H = C.
\end{flushleft}


˜


˜


\begin{flushleft}
Therefore, there exists a unique vector ($\xi$, $\eta$) $\in$ R2d such that
\end{flushleft}


(2.38)





\begin{flushleft}
$\pi$ (x, y) = ei($\xi$·x+$\eta$·y) IC .
\end{flushleft}


˜





\begin{flushleft}
Consider ﬁrst the case $\lambda$ = 0. From (2.36) e (2.37), taking the diﬀerential, it follows
\end{flushleft}


(2.39)





\begin{flushleft}
d$\pi$(T ) = i$\lambda$IH .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
In particular d$\pi$(T ) is a bounded operator. But we also know that for every j = 1, . . . , d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
it holds [Qj , Pj ] = $-$T , so that it must be
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
[d$\pi$(Qj ), d$\pi$(Pj )] = $-$d$\pi$(T ) = $-$i$\lambda$IH .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
By modifying Theorem 1.28 in the case of a multiple of the identity (the detatils are
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
left as an exercise) we see that the operators d$\pi$(Qj ) and d$\pi$(Pj ) cannot be both
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
bounded and, in particular, the representation space H cannot be ﬁnite dimensional.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
In conclusion, every unitary and irreducible representation of Hd which is not trivial
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
on the center is necessarily inﬁnite dimensional.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The next step consists in looking for the unitary and irreducible representations of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Hd that are not trivial on the center. The most natural way to go about it is to
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
compare the commutation Heisenberg relations with (1.24). We shall start from a very
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
natural representation of the Lie algebra hd and then use some heuristics, together
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
with Stone's Theorem, in order to get the corresponding representation of the group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
To this end, we introduce a useful Lie subalgebra of the Lie algebra of all diﬀerential
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
operators with polynomial coeﬃcients on Rd .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Let PD(Rd ) denote the vector space of all diﬀerential operators with polynomial
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
coeﬃcients on Rd . Under composition, it is an associative algebra generated by the 2d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
elements
\end{flushleft}


$\partial$


\begin{flushleft}
Dj = $-$
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
, Mj = (2$\pi$i)xj , j = 1, . . . , d.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\partial$xj
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
\newpage
Heisenberg group
\end{flushleft}





25





\begin{flushleft}
As any other associative algebra, PD(Rd ) becomes a Lie algebra if we deﬁne the bracket
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
as the commutator, that is [A, B] = A ◦ B $-$ B ◦ A. The generators Dj and Mj ,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
together with the operator {``}2$\pi$i--times the identity, give rise to a ﬁnite dimensional
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Lie subalgebra of PD(Rd ) which is isomorphic to hd . Indeed, the correspondence
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Dj $\rightarrow$ Qj , Mj $\rightarrow$ Pj and (2$\pi$i)I $\rightarrow$ T establishes the isomorphism. This isomorphism
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is actually a faithful (i.e. injective) representation of the Heisenberg algebra and should
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
be thought of as the diﬀerential of the representation we are looking for. In order to
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
ﬁnd the representation space, it will then be enough to ﬁnd a Hilbert space of functions
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
on Rd on which the operators we are dealing with are skew-adjoint. Finally, we shall
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
exponentiate the representation of hd .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Let H = L2 (Rd ) and D = S(Rd ), the Schwartz space of rapidly decreasing functions.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Both the derivations Dj and the multiplications Mj are densely deﬁned on H since
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
D is a natural common domain for them, which is dense in H. The operators are
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
formally skew-adjoint because for every ϕ, $\psi$ $\in$ S(Rd ) we have
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Mj ϕ, $\psi$ = $-$ ϕ, Mj $\psi$ ,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Dj ϕ, $\psi$ = $-$ ϕ, Dj $\psi$ ,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
where we are using L2 inner products and, in the second, integration by parts.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Observe that in order to deﬁne representations on the Heisenberg group it is not
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
necessary to specify the skew-adjoint extensions of Mj and of Dj . It will be suﬃcient
