h = 0, and that if h = h , then the corresponding representations are inequivalent.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The following celebrated theorem by Stone and von Neumann is of fundamental
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
importance in harmonic analysis: it states that the representations that we have built
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
so far exhaust, up to equivalence, the class of unitary and irreducible representation of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Hd . For a proof, see, for example, [F2].
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 2.4. (Stone--von Neumann) Every unitary and irreducible representation of Hd is unitarily equivalent to either one of the one--dimensional representations
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(2.38), or to a Schr¨dinger representation $\pi$h deﬁned in (2.44).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
o
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
It is worth observing that the determination of the Planck's constant is very simple:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
just compute the representation on the central elements (0, 0, t): by (2.44) this must
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
be just e2$\pi$ht I .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
2.3. Time-frequency analysis. In this section we indicate the basic role that the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
representation theory of the Heisenberg group plays in time-frequency analysis, in
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
particular in the deﬁnition and study of the so-called short-time Fourier transform
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(often abbreviated in STFT). The basic reference on this topic is the book [Gro] by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
K. Gr¨chenig.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
o
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The most basic operations in time-frequency analysis are the shifts in time and in
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
frequency. For x, $\omega$ $\in$ Rd and f $\in$ L2 (Rd ), we deﬁne the time shift by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Tx f (t) = f (t $-$ x),
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
x, t $\in$ Rd
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
and the frequency shift by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
M$\omega$ f ($\xi$) = e2$\pi$i$\omega$·$\xi$ f ($\xi$),
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
$\xi$, $\omega$ $\in$ Rd .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
It should be quite clear that there is no need to assume f $\in$ L2 (Rd ) in order for formulae
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(2.3) and (2.3) to make sense, but this is just to ﬁx some function space to work with.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
It is a matter of simple computation to establish a diﬀerent, but very closely related,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
version of the canonical commutaion relations, namely
\end{flushleft}


(2.45)





\begin{flushleft}
Tx M$\omega$ = e$-$2$\pi$ix·$\omega$ M$\omega$ Tx .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
It follows in particular that Tx and M$\omega$ commute if and only if x · $\omega$ $\in$ Z. Furthermore,
\end{flushleft}


ˆ


\begin{flushleft}
writing f for the Fourier transform Ff deﬁned as in (2.42), using the well-known
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
properties of Ff we have the formulae
\end{flushleft}


ˆ


ˆ


(2.46)


\begin{flushleft}
(Tx f )ˆ= M$-$x f ,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(M$\omega$ f )ˆ= T$\omega$ f .
\end{flushleft}





\newpage
28





\begin{flushleft}
The use of representations
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
From these it follows what is to be regarded as the most important formula in timefrequency analysis, namely
\end{flushleft}


ˆ


ˆ


(2.47)


\begin{flushleft}
(Tx M$\omega$ f )ˆ= M$-$x T$\omega$ f = e$-$2$\pi$ix·$\omega$ T$\omega$ M$-$x f ,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
whose proof is is left as an exercise.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The short-time Fourier transform is a mathematical device that is meant to capture
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the local contributions to the Fourier transform of a given function: one restricts the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
function to a small intervall by a cut-oﬀ function (preferably some smooth window)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and then takes the Fourier transform; by sliding the interval, one sees what are the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
various contributions from diﬀerent regions of the time domain. Formally, we have:
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Deﬁnition 2.5. Let $\eta$ = 0 be a ﬁxed window, that is, a function deﬁned on Rd . The
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
short-time Fourier transform of the function f : Rd $\rightarrow$ C with respect to $\eta$ is deﬁned
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
by
\end{flushleft}


(2.48)





\begin{flushleft}
f (y)$\eta$(y $-$ x)e$-$i$\xi$·y dy,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
V$\eta$ f (x, $\xi$) =
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
x, $\xi$ $\in$ Rd
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Rd
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
whenever the integral makes sense.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
A most fundamental observation is that the STFT is a function on the so-called
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
phase-space, namely the 2d-space R2d in which times and frequencies simultaneously
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
lie. In other words, in is a function of time and frequency. The time variable labels
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the {``}center'' of the window and the frequency labels the point at which the Fourier
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
transform is evaluated.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
At this stage we do not insist much on the precise domains for $\eta$ or for f . The most
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
basic properties of the STFT are given in the result that follows. The proof is easy.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 2.6. If f, $\eta$ $\in$ L2 (Rd ), then V$\eta$ f is uniformly continuous in R2d and
\end{flushleft}


(2.49)


(2.50)





\begin{flushleft}
V$\eta$ f (x, $\xi$) = F(f · Tx $\eta$)($\xi$)
\end{flushleft}





(2.51)





\begin{flushleft}
= f, M$\xi$ Tx $\eta$
\end{flushleft}


ˆ


\begin{flushleft}
= f , T$\xi$ M$-$x $\eta$
\end{flushleft}


ˆ





(2.52)





ˆ


\begin{flushleft}
= e$-$2$\pi$ix$\xi$ V$\eta$ f ($\xi$, $-$x).
\end{flushleft}


ˆ





\begin{flushleft}
Some comments. Formula (2.49) says what the STFT really is, the Fourier transform of a localized version of f . Formulae (2.50) and (2.51) indicate that it looks
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
formally like the coeﬃcient of some representation. Formula (2.52) exhibits a most
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
intriguing symmetry in time and frequency, together with a ninety-degree rotation
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(x, $\xi$) $\rightarrow$ ($\xi$, $-$x) in phase-space.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Before we pass to discuss the very intimate relation between the Heisenberg group
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and its representations and the STFT, we point out in the next three results the strong
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
features of the STFT.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 2.7 (Orthogonality relations for the STFT). Let f1 , f2 , $\eta$1 , $\eta$2 $\in$ L2 (Rd ).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Then V$\eta$j fj $\in$ L2 (R2d ) for j = 1, 2 and
\end{flushleft}


(2.53)





\begin{flushleft}
V$\eta$1 f1 , V$\eta$2 f2 = f1 , f2 $\eta$1 , $\eta$2 .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
