\begin{flushleft}
The use of representations
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
3. The metaplectc representation
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The meteplectic representation is a double-valued unitary representation of the symplectic group Sp(d, R) on L2 (Rd ), or, more technically speaking, a unitary representation of the double cover of Sp(d, R), otherwise known as the metaplectic group Mp(d).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
It has many other names in the literature, such as the oscillator representation, or the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Segal-Shale-Weil representation, and it appears pervasively in mathematics. We point
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
out right from the start that it is not irreducible: both the spaces L2 (Rd ) and L2 (Rd )
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
e
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
o
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
of even and odd functions, respectively, are closed and invariant, and on each of them
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the metaplectic representation is irreducible. In very practical terms, the metaplectic
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
representation assigns to each symplectic matrix a unitary operator on L2 (Rd ), which
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is well-deﬁned only up to a sign. This ambiguity, though mathematically important
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and not removable, plays a very mild role, if none at all, in many of the applications
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
that many people are concerned with in Applied Harmonic Analysis. In particular,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
this ambiguity is irrelevant in the context of the so-called reproducing formulae.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
As hinted in the previous paragraph, the very deﬁnition of the metaplectic representation is troublesome, and there are diﬀerent ways of going about it. For a thorough
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
presentation of this topic, the reader is referred either to [F2] or [LV]. Here we content ourselves with a discussion of the main features rather than delving into the full
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
machinery of proofs.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
We start by summarizing the main properties of the symplectic group and of its Lie
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
algebra. A direct and easy proof of most of the statements may be found in [F2]. The
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
most advanced ones, such as for example the Iwasawa decomposition, can be found for
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
example in [K1].
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
3.1. The symplectic group. The symplectic group is the group of invertible 2d × 2d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
matrices preserving the standard symplectic form $\omega$ : R2d × R2d $\rightarrow$ R deﬁned by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\omega$(x, y) = txJy,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
J=
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
0 Id
\end{flushleft}


.


\begin{flushleft}
$-$Id 0
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Thus, a matrix g $\in$ GL(2d, R) is symplectic if and only if $\omega$(gx, gy) = $\omega$(x, y) for every
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
x, y $\in$ R2d , so that the group of all of them is therefore
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
