\begin{flushleft}
Exercise 1. Show that an invertible matrix g satisﬁes $\omega$(gx, gy) = $\omega$(x, y) for every
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
x, y $\in$ R2d if and only if tgJg = J
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Exercise 2. Show that M , A and N are indeed subgroups of Sp(d, R). Show that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
M A is a group and that it normalizes N , that is, that xnx$-$1 $\in$ N whenever x $\in$ M A
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and n $\in$ N . Show also that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
N = tn : n $\in$ N
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
is a subgroup of Sp(d, R).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
As any other semisimple5 group, the symplectic group admits a polar decomposition
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
as stated in the following proposition.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 3.1. (Polar decomposition) Any invertible matrix g can be written
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
uniquely as g = up, where u is orthogonal and p is positive deﬁnite. If g $\in$ Sp(d, R),
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
then both u and p are in Sp(d, R). Furthermore, p $\in$ Sp(d, R) is positive deﬁnite if
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and only if p = exp S with S $\in$ sp(d, R) $\cap$ Sym(2d, R).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The following fact is very important.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 3.2. K = Sp(d, R) $\cap$ O(2d) is a maximal compact subgroup of Sp(d, R)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
and it is isomorphic to the unitary group U (d) under the natural map induced on linear
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
maps by the identiﬁcation (x, y) $\rightarrow$ x + iy of R2d with Cd .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
A direct consequence of the previous two propositions is the following statement
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
about the main topological features of the symplectic group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 3.3. The symplectic group is connected but not simply connected; its
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
fundamental group is Z.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Again, the theorem that follows is a particular instance of a much more general
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
theorem, valid for all semisimple (in fact reductive) groups.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
5The
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
symplectic group belongs to the very important class of semisimple Lie groups. Here we are
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
not interested in this particular aspect and shall not introduce this notion. The reader is referred to
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
[K1] and [K2] for a detailed discussion of semisimple Lie groups an their representations.
\end{flushleft}





