\begin{flushleft}
The use of representations
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Theorem 3.4. (Iwasawa decomposition) The following factorizations hold true:
\end{flushleft}


(3.57)





\begin{flushleft}
Sp(d, R) = KAN = KN A = AN K = N AK.
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
This means that any g $\in$ Sp(d, R) may be written uniquely as g = kan with k $\in$ K ,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
a $\in$ A and n $\in$ N . Similarly for the other products, with possibly diﬀerent factors.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
A little attention must be paid to the last sentence. In short, we may write a group
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
element g either as g = kan or as g = $\alpha$$\nu$$\kappa$, with a, $\alpha$ $\in$, n, $\nu$ $\in$ N and k, $\kappa$ $\in$ K . In
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
general, though, a = $\alpha$ and similarly for the other factors. But if we write g = k a n
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(same order) then necessarily k = k , a = a and n = n .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Exercise 3. Show that the product N A is in fact a group itself, whereas neither of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the products KA or KN is a group.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Proposition 3.5. The symplectic group is generated by N $\cup$ M A $\cup$ \{J\} and also by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
N $\cup$ M A $\cup$ \{J\}.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
The meaning of the above statements is that any element in Sp(d, R) can be written
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
as a ﬁnite product of elements all taken from N $\cup$ M A $\cup$ \{J\}, or all taken from
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
N $\cup$ M A $\cup$ \{J\}. This fact is of practical relevance, as we shall see, when dealing with
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the metaplectic representation.
\end{flushleft}


