\begin{flushleft}
3.2. Construction of the metaplectic representation. We now proceed to deﬁne
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
the metaplectic representation abstractly. Later we indicate how one can go about
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
clearing out all the unsettled points.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Recall that the group T of automorphisms of the Heisenberg group that leave the
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
center poinwise ﬁxed is generated by the inner automorphisms and by the symplectic
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
maps. More precisely, the maps ih with h $\in$ Hd and Tg with g $\in$ Sp(d, R) given by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
i(x,y,z) (q, p, t) = (x, y, z)$-$1 (q, p, t)(x, y, z) = (q, p, t + ap $-$ bq)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Tg (q, p, t) = (g(q, p), t),
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
where g(q, p) simply means the eﬀect of the linear map g on the vector (q, p) $\in$ R2d .
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
If T $\in$ T , we can precompose the Schr¨dinger representation $\pi$ with T to obtain a
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
o
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
d
\end{flushleft}


2


\begin{flushleft}
d
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
new representation $\pi$ ◦ T of H on L (R ). Indeed, if h, k $\in$ Hd , then
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
($\pi$ ◦ T )(hk) = $\pi$(T (hk)) = $\pi$(T (h)T (K)) = $\pi$(T (h))$\pi$(T (k)) = ($\pi$ ◦ T )(h)($\pi$ ◦ T )(k)
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
shows that it is indeed a representation and furthermore (2.41) shows that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
($\pi$ ◦ T )(0, 0, t) = $\pi$(T (0, 0, t)) = $\pi$(0, 0, t) = e2$\pi$it I.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
By the Stone-von Neumann theorem, $\pi$ and $\pi$ ◦ T must be equivalent. Hence there
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
must be a unitary operator $\mu$(T ) on L2 (Rd ) that intertwines the two representations:
\end{flushleft}


(3.59)





\begin{flushleft}
$\pi$ ◦ T (h) = $\mu$(T )$\pi$(h)$\mu$(T )$-$1 ,
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
h $\in$ Hd .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
Moreover, by Schur's Lemma, namely item ii) of Lemma 1.25, $\mu$(T ) is determined
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
up to a phase factor because the space I($\pi$, $\pi$ ◦ T ) of all intertwining operators is
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
one dimensional and contains a unitary operator, hence all its multiples by complex
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
numbers of modulus one. Now, if we write (3.59) for the product T S we ﬁnd that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\mu$(T )$\mu$(S) does the job, so there exists cT,S $\in$ S 1 such that
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\mu$(T S) = cT,S $\mu$(T )$\mu$(S).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
This means that $\mu$ deﬁnes a projective representation of T , that is, a homomorphis
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
into the quotient of the group of unitary operators modulo its center \{cI : c $\in$ S 1 \}.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Now, if T = ih , with h $\in$ Hd , then since
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\pi$(hgh$-$1 ) = $\pi$(h)$\pi$(g)$\pi$(h)$-$1 ,
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
we can certainly take $\mu$(ih ) = $\pi$(h). Thus we may restrict ourselves to the subgroup
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
of T consisting of the automorphisms Tg with g $\in$ Sp(d, R), a group manifestly
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
isomorphic to Sp(d, R) itself. We shall write for simplicity $\mu$(g) instead of $\mu$(Tg ).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
From the above discussion it follows that the unitary operator $\mu$(g) is determined up
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
to a phase factor by the relation
\end{flushleft}


(3.60)





\begin{flushleft}
$\pi$(g(q, p), 0) = $\mu$(g)$\pi$(q, p, 0)$\mu$(g)$-$1 .
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
It may be shown (see below for further comments) that the phase factors can be chosen
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
in one and only one way up to a sign, so that $\mu$ becomes a double-valued unitary
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
representation of Sp(d, R). In other words, it holds
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
$\mu$(gh) = $\pm$$\mu$(g)$\mu$(h),
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
g, h $\in$ Sp(d, R).
\end{flushleft}





\newpage
34





\begin{flushleft}
The use of representations
\end{flushleft}





\begin{flushleft}
With this choice, $\mu$ is called the metaplectic representation.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
We should either think of $\mu$ as a genuine unitary representatin of the double cover
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Mp(d) of Sp(d, R) or as a homomorphism of Sp(d, R) into the quotient of the group of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
unitary operators modulo its center \{$\pm$I\}.Given a single g $\in$ Sp(d, R), we may think
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
of $\mu$(g) as a pir of unitary operators that diﬀer from each other by $-$1. In explicit
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
formulas, this amniguity usually appears as the possible choice of sign of a square root.
\end{flushleft}


