\begin{flushleft}
It must be pointed out that in formulae (3.61) and (3.63) the sign of the square root
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
accounts exactly for the ambiguity in sign.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
3.3. An outline of the full construction. The question remains: how to deﬁne $\mu$
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
in full detail? Our next target is to outline how to do this. The several nontrivial
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
technicalities will not be unravelled completely. The construction can be summarized
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
in the following three basic steps, for each of which we will then give some further
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
information.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(i) Deﬁne ﬁrst the inﬁnitesimal representation d$\mu$ of the Lie algebra sp(d, R) by
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
densely deﬁned unbounded and essentially skew-adjoint operators on L2 (Rd ).
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
This step is obtained by means of the so calle Weyl calculus, realizing ﬁrst
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
sp(d, R) as a Lie algebra of polynomials.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(ii) {``}Integrate'' the representation to a representation of the universal cover of
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
Sp(d, R). This step uses the notion of analytic vector for a representation.
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
(iii) Show that the represntation actually factors to a representation of the double
\end{flushleft}


\begin{flushleft}
cover of Sp(d, R).
\end{flushleft}





